Bad to the bone
The case for the downfall of third party delivery begins and ends with the =
business model.=C2=A0Peter Drucker refers to a business model as =E2=80=9Ca=
ssumptions about what a company gets paid for.=E2=80=9D Today=E2=80=99s thi=
rd party delivery operators make the following assumption:
Restaurants will pay 30% of revenue for new customers, serviced by a third =
party delivery network.
This sounds reasonable. A few extra meals a night to new customers would be=
tter utilize existing resources and make the restaurant more profitable.=C2=
=A0A nice story, but not true.
While sales representatives from DoorDash and UberEats tell restaurateurs t=
hey are paying for new customers, in reality they know they will also be ch=
arged 30% to service existing and repeat customers, too.=C2=A0Industry data=
 first shared with Expedite [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEmOhDAMR=
U9T2YHIwFCLLHrT10AOMRAVJChxmub2nSoWLXmQbH19-01AuIR46SMkYu8y0nWg9nimDYkwspww=
