bsp;This reduction in cost encouraged restaurants to fire their delivery em=
ployees and deepen their reliance on third party delivery.</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">The =
integration of the food delivery value chain has come at a cost to restaura=
nts.&nbsp;In order for DoorDash and UberEats to enjoy attractive profits fo=
r themselves, they take them from restaurants.&nbsp;After all there is only=
 so much profit to go around on a cheeseburger with free delivery.</p><p st=
yle=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em =
0;">Independent restaurants are all but powerless to negotiate fees, as man=
y have relinquished their own proprietary ordering, payments, and delivery =
systems to work with these platforms.&nbsp;The platforms feel no need to ne=
gotiate, confident that if one restaurant leaves, another will take its pla=
ce to satisfy a hungry diner.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">It is for this reason that in 202=
0, when the COVID-19 pandemic hit, nearly every restaurant in America paid =
a 30% tariff to the third party delivery overlords, and what was already a =
bad deal became unbearable.</p><h3 style=3D"-moz-osx-font-smoothing: antial=
